		["autotransport_menu"] = "Car transport wagons (Cargo)",
		["autotransport_person_menu"] = "Car transport wagons (Passengers)",
		["autotransport_person_fake_menu"] = "Car transport wagons (Passengers) Fake",
		["autotransport_fake_menu"] = "Car transport wagons (Cargo) FAKE",

		["xfm_desc"] = "The generic designation XWagen originally stood for work car. Since there was no money to be made with these cars, the railroad administrations were anxious to procure or prepare X cars as inexpensively as possible. Nothing was more obvious than to convert old cars of various types for this purpose. Since at the beginning of the 50s special car transport cars were not yet available, it was necessary - in order to provide sufficient capacity - to use X(f) cars on a large scale in addition to R(o), S and SS cars.",
		["offs52_desc"] = "From December 1953 to March 1954, 600 cars were diverted from Omm 52 production to make car transport cars. Since two cars formed a unit, there were 300 Off 52s. By 1967, the cars had been converted back into Omm 52s.",
		["Laes547_desc"] = "In 1964, Graaff built three pre-production cars of a three-axle car transport unit, designated Laes 547 from 1965. They could be fully lowered individually for transporting tall vehicles. DB AG received another 1,035 cars, which were retired from the stock between 2005 and 2012. In addition, there was an almost identical version for passenger service, designated as Offehss 548. They were designed for 120 km/h and had continuous heating lines, the flat upper loading area was secured by a railing with two ropes. All of the cars came to DB AG and were last used between Lehrte and Berlin-Grunewald in 1995.",
		["Offhs66_desc"] = "For the Westerland service between Niebüll and Westerland on the island of Sylt, special double-deck cars were built after simple flat cars.From 1964 to 1970, Graaf built twelve nine-car Offs 549 / Laaes 549. The end sections corresponded to Offs 547, with seven identical center cars running between them with single-axle undercarriages for two cars each. Between 1961 and 1979, a total of 30 Off(h)s 66 - from 1965 Le(r)s 544 - were built as end cars for Westerland units on underframes of Rlmms 58/Kbs 443. All cars came to DB AG and were replaced in 2002.",

		["DDm915_gruen_name"] = "DDm 915 DB (DB bottle green) [1968]",
		["DDm915_grun2_name"] = "DDm 915 DB (DB bottle green) [1994]",
		["DDm915_ozeanblau_name"] = "DDm 915 (DB ocean blue) [1975]",
		["DDm915_fernblau_name"] = "DDm 915 (DB distant blue) [1987]",
		["DDm915_fernblau_name"] = "DDm 915 (DB distant blue) [1994]",
		["DDm915_verkehrsrot_name"] = "DDm 915 (DB Autozug [1999])",
		["DDm915_rotGrau_name"] = "DDm 915 (DB Autozug white-red) [1999]",
		["DDm915_desc"] = "Starting in 1969, 165 DDm 915 open double-decker cars were manufactured by the Graaff and Uerdingen car manufacturing companies. These cars can carry five passenger cars on each of the two levels and use special ramps to allow loading and unloading. They are 26.4 meters long, weigh an average of 27.8 tons and have a maximum speed of 160 km/h. The cars are mounted on Minden-Deutz bogies and some of them are equipped with magnetic rail brakes.",
		["DD_oebb_desc"] = "In 1971, the Austrian Federal Railways took ten DDm 98-80 cars into service from Waggonfabrik Uerdingen, which closely resembled the DB's DDm915. Between 1982 and 1990, eighty further developed DDm 98-70 cars were built at Jenbacher Werke, the first 40 of which were painted in Eurofima C1 livery.",

		["DDm916_fernblau_name"] = "DDm 916 (DB distant blue) [1994]",
		["DDm916_desc"] = "In the 1960s, the SNCF introduced Trains Auto-couchettes (T.A.C), which allowed passengers to take their cars with them. The SNCF ordered type DD 66 double-deck cars from ANF-Frangeco, which were capable of speeds of up to 160 km/h. Similar cars were also purchased in Germany, Spain and Belgium. In the 1970s, the Deutsche Reichsbahn purchased 38 DDm916 cars from ANF Frangeco in France for motorail trains from West Berlin to the south and from Dresden to Budapest. Some were painted IR blue, others traffic red, while most remained green. Many of these cars were later sold abroad or to private companies.",

		["laaers3000d6_desc"] = "The Laaers 3000D6 car transport wagons were delivered to NMBS by Vagonka Poprad in September 1993. A total of 300 units were ordered in cooperation with Cobelfret and British Rail. These wagons are 31 meters long and weigh 21.5 tons empty. Originally intended for the Channel Tunnel, they were taken over by Cobelfret and mainly used for car transportation, especially for Ford. ARS Altmann later integrated some wagons from the Cobelfret fleet into its fleet.",

		["laaers560_desc"] = "As a development of the Laaeks 553, Graaff built a pre-series of 36 two-part double-deck car transport wagons in 2007/08. From 2009, series production took place at Waggonbau Niesky, yielding approximately 650 lightly modified wagons. These featured Knorr brakes and a modified mechanism for raising and lowering the upper deck. The final deliveries were completed in 2013.",
		["Offs55_desc"] = "In 955, Graaff developed the Offs 55 as the first three-axle car transport unit and built 1,200 wagons by 1959, from 1965 as Laes 542, then from 1981 as Laekkms 542. From 1988, 150 Laekkms 542 were turned into units of 25 wagons each for VW block train services. Their overrunning flaps, which remained in the overrunning position even during the journey, were shortened and the wheel chocks removed. On other wagons, which also only ran in fixed train formations, the wheel wells were filled up for the transportation of cars with a wide track. 410 Laekkms 542 - used by ATG since 1991 - were sent to DB AG, which took them out of service completely by 1999.",
		["mgc_desc"] = "The Laeks MEGACARs are the result of the conversion of Laeks wagons owned by Transfesa, which were integrated into the HISPANAUTO pool. The original wagons were manufactured by SNAV in 1973/74. In addition, Lails, Lais and Lags were also used by Transfesa, which had the same type of bogies with three axles and were also built by SNAV between 1976 and 1979. Laeks 24 71 4273 001 to 140 were produced by TAFESA in 2006, while Laeks 24 71 4273 141 to 299 were produced by TRANSERVI from 2007.",
		["laaers224_desc"] = "In 1977/78, the Ceská Lípa wagon factory (Czech Republic) built(Czech Republic) built 300 two-axle double-decker car transport wagons for the DR for transporting cars, classified as Leks [4180]. Some of these wagons were rebuilt and modernized by ARS Altmann in the early 1990s and classified as Laaers 224Sb. A further modernization took place in the mid-2000s as type Laaers 224Sc.",
		["laaersABRF_desc"] = "In the mid-2000s, the former French wagon manufacturer supplied wagon units of the Laaers type with grid protection, which were leased by companies such as BLG, Touax and Mosolf.",
		["laaes553_desc"] = "In 1980, Graaff developed two car transport wagons, Laaeks 553, for transporting cars. Each wagon consists of short-coupled single wagons with a maximum loading height of 1.71 m on the lower level. Between 1986 and 1990, 2,152 wagons were produced in series by various companies, with slight differences in the shape of the wagon ends. Most of the wagons, managed by ATG since 1991, were taken over by DB AG, and so far fewer than 20 have been taken out of service. In 1995, an additional eight Laaes 553 were added, built in 1986 by WU Berlin for Norwegian companies, sometimes incorrectly labeled as Laaeks 553.",
		["laaes556_desc"] = "ATG Autotransportlogistic GmbH was founded in 1990 through the cooperation of IVG, TWA and VTG. In cooperation with DWA Niesky and LHB, a total of 200 car transport units, Laaes 556, were built for VTG, IVG and TWA in 1992. These consist of two short-coupled wagons with the same dimensions as the Laaeks 553 and are designed for a speed of 120 km/h. The wagons were originally used by the DR, from 1994 by DB AG and are managed by ATG (since 2011 DB Schenker Rail Automotive). In 2004, the ownership of the former IVG wagons changed and they became genuine DB AG wagons.",
		["Offhs66_desc"] = "For the traffic between Niebüll and Westerland on the island of Sylt, after simple flatcars, special double-deck cars were produced. From 1964 to 1970, Graaf built twelve nine-part Offs 549 / Laaes 549. The end sections were similar to Offs 547, with seven identical middle cars featuring individual axle assemblies for every two cars. As end cars for Westerland units, a total of 30 Off(h)s 66 were built between 1961 and 1979 – rebranded as Le(r)s 544 from 1965 – using underframes from Rlmms 58/Kbs 443. All these wagons were transferred to DB AG and were replaced in 2002.",

